# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: denver
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:denver/105th-meridian-west] The **meridian 105° west of Greenwich** is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, North America, the Pacific Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:denver/105th-meridian-west] The 105th meridian west forms a great circle with the 75th meridian east.
[src:denver/105th-meridian-west] It serves as the reference meridian for the seventh time zone west of Greenwich, known as UTC-07 or the Mountain Time Zone in North America.
[src:denver/105th-meridian-west] In the United States, Interstate Highway I-25 roughly parallels the meridian from Douglas, Wyoming to Las Vegas, New Mexico, and from Wellington, Colorado to the Prospect Road interchange (in Fort Collins, Colorado), I-25 happens to be almost exactly aligned along the 105th meridian west.
[src:denver/105th-meridian-west] The meridian bisects Denver, Colorado, passing through Denver Union Station.
[src:denver/105th-meridian-west] Throughout the Denver metro area, Kalamath Street is the road that most closely corresponds to the 105th meridian.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] For Denver, 16th Street has long been an important commercial street.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] In the 1960s it was lined with movie theaters, department stores, banks, and retail outlets.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] However, by the 1970s, downtown Denver faced severe bus congestion on 16th and 17th streets, more than 600 daily trips, contributing to air pollution and traffic congestion.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] The area's design also discouraged pedestrian activity.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] To address these issues, the downtown business community and the Regional Transportation District (RTD) proposed building bus transfer stations at Market Street and Broadway, connected by a pedestrian mall with a free shuttle bus service.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] Pei & Partners in collaboration with the urban design and landscape architecture firm OLIN.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] Construction was funded by a US$75 million grant (equivalent to $293.1 million in 2025) from Federal Interstate Highway Transfer Funds and the Federal Urban Mass Transit Administration, with RTD providing a local match.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] The original 12+1⁄2-block, 4⁄5-mile (1.3 km) 16th Street Mall is considered a landmark of late-20th-century design, combining post–World War II Modernist geometry and lighting with Postmodern references to western motifs.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] Its granite paving—19-inch (48 cm) square blocks in charcoal gray, light gray, and "Colorado red"—forms a diamond pattern inspired by Navajo blankets and diamondback rattlesnake skin.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] Other unique elements include distinctive light standards, northern red oaks and honey locust trees in engineered root boxes, fiberglass street furniture, and metal signage.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] After two years of construction, the Mall opened on October 4, 1982, with a ceremony that drew more than 200,000 visitors downtown.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] The Mall initially ran from Market Street Station to Civic Center Station at Broadway.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] Consolidating shuttle service along the route removed about 870 daily bus trips from surrounding streets, by funneling express and regional commuter buses to the bus stations.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] The Federal Transit Administration classifies the mall as a "fixed guideway", enabling RTD to receive operating funds under the same formula as a rail line.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] In 1994, the addition of light rail service on California and Stout streets added a third transit hub to the mall.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] The improvements on the street were extended three block into Lower Downtown in 1994 reaching Wynkoop Street, which included the demolition of the 16th Street Viaduct.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] Four more blocks into the Central Platte Valley district were added in 2012 ending at Wewatta Street.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] These extensions feature wide sidewalks and streetscape upgrades but not the older Mall's granite paving, reaching a total length of 1+1⁄4-mile (2.0 km) and 18+1⁄2-blocks.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] However, the segment from Wewatta to Wynkoop Streets is partly open to local vehicle traffic.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] RTD purchased Union Station in 2001 and started the process of redeveloping the historic station along with 19.85 acres (8.03 ha) of land in LoDo, to create a new transit hub that would replace Market Street Station.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] To enable the project, the Free MallRide was extended west from Market Street to Wynkoop Street that year and to Union Station in 2002, coinciding with the opening of a new light rail spur.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] In 2014, RTD opened an underground bus concourse at Union Station and closed Market Street Station.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] The land was sold to a developer for $11 million, which helped fund the redevelopment of Union Station, and the station site was transformed into a mixed-use building with residential, office, retail and restaurant space.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] By the 2010s, the granite paving was showing significant deterioration, prompting multiple studies calling for comprehensive reconstruction.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] In April 2022, work began on a $149 million rebuild, with a planned completion date of fall 2025.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] Of the 199 honey locust trees and 83 northern red oaks of the original mall, only 143 locusts were still alive and the majority of the oaks had died by 2023.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] The remaining trees were nearing the end of their lifespan and removed and replanted with new honey locusts as well as overcup oaks, swamp white oaks, Kentucky coffeetrees, 'Morton' elms, and 'Morton' Miyabe maples.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] The renovation project concluded in 2025 with a cerebration of the reopening on October 4.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] With the end of the project it was officially renamed as simply 16th Street, dropping mall from the name of the pedestrian portion of the street.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] The 16th Street FreeRide is a free shuttle bus service operated by the RTD along the length of the 16th Street Mall, with buses stopping at every intersection.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] The service began in 1982 as the 16th Street MallRide, originally running between Market Street Station and Civic Center Station (16th & Broadway), two major RTD bus hubs at either end of downtown.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] In 1994, light rail transit service was added at 16th & California and 16th & Stout stations, creating a third transit hub along the mall.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] In 2011, the route was extended north of the mall on 16th Street to Denver Union Station.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] In 2014, Market Street Station was closed and replaced by the Union Station Transit Center.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] In 2025, coinciding with the dropping of "Mall" from the 16th Street Mall name, the service was renamed 16th Street FreeRide.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] As of 2024, the route provides connections between the A Line, B Line, E Line, G Line, N Line, and W Line and the bus hub at Denver Union Station; the D Line, H Line, and L Line at 16th & California and 16th & Stout stations; and the bus hub at Civic Center Station.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] In 2018, the route saw an average weekday ridership of 43,971, making it the busiest operated by RTD.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] Buses operate from 5:30 a.m. to midnight on weekdays, with slightly shorter service hours on weekends and holidays.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] During peak periods, shuttles can run as frequently as every 90 seconds, with service reduced to every 10 minutes in the early morning and late evening.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] Since the service's inception, RTD has used custom-designed right-hand drive buses.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] This configuration gives operators improved visibility of passengers boarding and alighting from the curb side, as well as pedestrians who often move close to the buses, which travel at speeds up to 12 miles per hour (19 km/h) in the open mall setting.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] The buses also feature a low-floor design with an open interior with minimal seating (currently 18 seats, out of a capacity of 106), and three doors, enabling near-level boarding and accommodating fast passenger flow both inside the bus and during boarding and alighting.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] The first-generation buses, used from 1982 to 1999, were diesel-powered and front-wheel drive.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] The second-generation "EcoMark" buses, used from 1999 to 2016, were series hybrids with wheel hub motors powered by batteries charged from a 70 horsepower (52 kW), 1.6-liter compressed natural gas engine supplied by Ford.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] The third-generation BYD K10MR buses, introduced in 2016, are fully battery electric.
[src:denver/16th-street-mall] The Project for Public Spaces says of the Mall that it "provides the entire downtown with shuttle bus circulation and high quality pedestrian access to Union Station.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:denver/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:denver/1860s-p01] The **1860s** (pronounced "eighteen-sixties") was a decade of the Gregorian calendar that began on January 1, 1860 and ended on December 31, 1869.
[src:denver/1860s-p01] The decade was noted for featuring numerous major societal shifts in the Americas.
[src:denver/1860s-p01] In North America, the election of anti-slavery candidate Abraham Lincoln to the presidency in 1860 in the United States led to the secession of eleven southern states as the Confederate States of America (CSA).
[src:denver/1860s-p01] The resulting American Civil War (1861–1865) would be among the first industrial wars, featuring advanced technology such as steel warships and machine guns.
[src:denver/1860s-p01] The victory of the Union and subsequent abolition of slavery would contribute to the decline of the global slave trade.
[src:denver/1860s-p01] Conflict in Mexico ensued after the French Empire installed Maximilian I as Emperor of Mexico; former President Benito Suarez would regain his position in 1867 after a power struggle.
[src:denver/1860s-p01] In South America, the Triple Alliance of the Empire of Brazil, Argentina and Uruguay in the Paraguayan War (1864–1870) would be among the bloodiest conflicts in the continent's history, leading to the death of almost 60% of the Paraguayan population.
[src:denver/1860s-p01] In Europe, the formation of the union of Austria-Hungary in 1867 and the ongoing campaign to unify Italy by Victor Emmanuel II of Sardinia-Piedmont would affect the European balance of power.
[src:denver/1860s-p01] The United Kingdom would continue engaging in a series of conflicts known as the New Zealand Wars with the indigenous Māori, with the New Zealand land confiscations beginning in 1863.
[src:denver/1860s-p01] In Asia, the Meiji Restoration of 1868 would begin the process of transforming Japan into a global imperial power.
[src:denver/1860s-p01] The Qing Dynasty of China would experience decline following its defeat to the British in 1860 in the Second Opium War.
[src:denver/1860s-p01] In 1864, the Russian Empire would embark upon the Circassian genocide in the Caucasus, leading to the deaths or expulsion of at least 75% of the Circassian people.
[src:denver/1860s-p01] The last living person from this decade was Nellie Spencer, who died on November 13, 1982.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:denver/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] The **1880 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office during June 1880, was the tenth United States census.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] It was the first time that women were permitted to be enumerators.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] The Superintendent of the Census was Francis Amasa Walker.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York City—recorded a population of over one million, and the first census in which the 20 most populated cities all recorded over 100,000 residents.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] Schedule 4 (Social statistics) was the responsibility of experts and special agents, rather than the enumerators.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] The majority of the data came from correspondence with officials of institutions providing care and treatment of certain members of the population.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] Experts and special agents also were employed to collect data on valuation, taxation, and indebtedness; religion and libraries; colleges, academies, and schools; newspapers and periodicals, and wages.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1880 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series, which contains microdata.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau; after which the original sheets were transferred to various state archives, libraries, or universities.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along which digital indices.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1880 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census determined the resident population of the United States to be 50,189,209, an increase of 30.2 percent over the 38,555,983 persons enumerated during the 1870 census.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] The mean center of United States population for 1880 was in Boone County, Kentucky.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] The results from the census were used to determine the apportionment for the 48th, 49th, 50th, 51st, and 52nd sessions of the United States Congress.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] The processing of the 1880 census data took so long (eight years) that the Census Bureau contracted Herman Hollerith to design and build a tabulating machine to be used for the next census.
[src:denver/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census also led to the discovery of the Alabama paradox.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The choice of the permanent capital of the U.S. state of Colorado was put to a popular vote in 1881.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The cities in active contention were: Denver, Del Norte, Pueblo, Colorado Springs, Canon City, and Salida.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The City of Denver, which had been the temporary capital since Colorado became a state in 1876, was chosen by 66 percent of voters.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Although Denver City was always the largest town in the Territory of Colorado since its recognition in 1861, and then the state, admitted to the union in 1876, there were always those in the state who opposed putting the capital in Denver.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The first meeting of the Colorado territorial legislature, held in Denver in 1861, chose Colorado City (now part of Colorado Springs) as the capital.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] But when the legislature met in Colorado City for the first time in 1862, the facilities were so inadequate that after five days, the delegates voted to adjourn and reconvene in Denver.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] But when they reconvened in Denver, they chose not to stay there, and named Golden as the territorial capital.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Although Golden was officially the territorial capital, the legislature often met in Denver, because it was more of a city.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] In 1867, the legislature voted to move the state government to Denver.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Although Denver had enough influence to prevent the removal of the acting capital from Denver, there was also enough opposition to prevent it from being designated as the permanent capital.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] When Colorado drafted a constitution for admission as a state in 1876, the framers feared that if the state constitution designated any city as the permanent state capital, it would arouse enough opposition that the voters would not ratify the constitution.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] To solve the dilemma, the Colorado state constitution kicked the problem down the road by providing that a permanent state capital would be chosen by statewide popular vote five years later, in 1881.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Although Denver was a transportation hub, and had more than twice the population of the next-largest city in Colorado, four other cities put themselves forward as sites for the capital.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Denver's rivals hoped to use antipathy toward Denver to have themselves named as the capital.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Some of the larger towns in Colorado did not mount active campaigns for the capital.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Leadville, which in 1880 census was the second-most populous town in Colorado with a population of 14,820, showed no interest in becoming state capital.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Neither did Silver Cliff, then Colorado's third-largest with a population of 5,040.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Golden, which had hosted the territorial government from 1862 to 1867, did not try to win back the capital in 1881.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Denver had grown considerably since it became the temporary territorial capital.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The growth had been considerably aided by the establishment of a railroad connection in 1870, from Denver eastward, by the Kansas Pacific Railroad.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] This early rail connection made Denver the hub for movement of people and supplies to and from other points in Colorado.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Denver was far larger than any of its rivals for state capital.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Denver had enjoyed the economic stimulus of hosting the state government, and was eager to make it permanent.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] It had the advantage of being by far the largest town in Colorado.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Committees were formed to visit other parts of the state promoting Denver as the capital, and assuring other cities that Denver wanted only the capital, and in return, Denver would support the location of other institutions, such as the university and the school of mines, outside of Denver.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Businessman Henry Brown offered to donate ten acres near downtown Denver for a new state capitol building, if Denver were chosen to have it.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Denver supporters hailed the offer, and noted that the tract as an ideal spot, with a grand westward vista toward the mountains.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Detractors noted that Brown owned more real estate in the vicinity, which would jump in value if the state capitol building were to be nearby.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Colorado Springs was at the time the fourth most-populous town in Colorado, with 4,226 inhabitants.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Founded in 1871, it was growing rapidly, and touted its more genteel atmosphere compared to Denver.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Supporters noted that most older states had wisely located their capitals away from large commercial cities.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] In 1880, Pueblo had 3,217 inhabitants, not large enough to put it in the top five most populous towns in Colorado.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] But Pueblo had once come close to becoming the territorial capital.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] In 1874, the Colorado territorial house had passed a bill to make Pueblo the capital, but the measure was not passed by the territorial senate.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The *Pueblo Chieftain* maintained that Pueblo was the most pleasant city to place the capital, and had plenty of good hotels and restaurants to satisfy the legislators.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Canon City had a population of 1,501 in the 1880 census.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] It was principally a supply point on the Arkansas River for the mines and oil field.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] It promoted itself as having the most pleasant climate in the state.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] It was awarded the territorial prison after losing the contest for the Colorado state capital.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Salida had been founded just the preceding year, and had missed the 1880 census.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The campaign for state capital consisted of editorials in Salida's weekly newspaper, the *Mountain Mail*.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The *Mail* printed a distorted map of Colorado showing Salida in the exact geographical center.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The referendum was held on 8 November 1881.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] In each city vying for state capital, lopsided majorities voted for their hometowns.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] In Pueblo County, 2,039 voted for Pueblo, and just 44 for other towns.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Arapahoe County, of which Denver was then the county seat, held off releasing its count until nearly all of the other counties had reported, counted 8,839 votes for Denver, which were 99.8 percent of the 8,857 ballots counted.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Denver won on the first ballot, thus avoiding a runoff vote.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Denver was widely accused of buying votes, and bribing newspaper editors to back it for the state capital.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The editor of the Salida *Mountain Mail* congratulated Denver on its victory, and noted that Denver was a beautiful city that deserved the capital.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The editor confessed that the campaign for Salida was just a publicity stunt to bring the town to public attention, and that it had succeeded.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] He wrote that although Denver had spent "thousands of dollars, perhaps hundreds of thousands" bribing newspaper editors and hiring "bummers" to vote for Denver, the money had performed a public service by supporting newspapers and indigent citizens across the state.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Since 1881, local myths have grown that various other towns in Colorado were in serious contention to become state capital, among them: Central City, Cripple Creek, Fountain, Golden, Laporte, Leadville, and Silver Cliff.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The town of Cripple Creek was not even in existence until 1892, eleven years after the referendum.
[src:denver/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Webpages about Central City, Laporte, and Silver Cliff have claimed that not only were those towns in serious contention to be the state capital, but that each town lost the referendum to Denver by a single vote.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver's downtown district lies about 12 miles (19 kilometers) east of the foothills of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver, the governor of the Kansas Territory at the time, Denver was founded at the confluence of Cherry Creek and the South Platte River in 1858 during the Gold Rush era.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Nicknamed the "Mile High City" because its official elevation is exactly one mile (5280 feet or 1609.344 meters) above sea level, Denver grew beyond its prospecting origins to become the principal commercial and transportation hub for a broad region spanning the Great Plains and Rocky Mountain West.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The 105th meridian west of Greenwich, the longitudinal reference for the Mountain Time Zone, passes directly through Denver Union Station.
[src:denver/denver-p01] As the most populous metropolitan area in a 560-mile (900 km) radius, Denver is a major cultural hub with a variety of museums and cultural institutions, including the Denver Performing Arts Complex, the Denver Art Museum and the Denver Museum of Nature and Science.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver has professional sports teams in five leagues and hosts the headquarters of eight *Fortune* 500 firms.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The greater Denver area was inhabited by several Indigenous peoples such as Apaches, Utes, Cheyennes, Comanches, and Arapahoes.
[src:denver/denver-p01] This definition specifically encompasses the land of modern Metropolitan Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] But the discovery in November 1858 of gold in the Rocky Mountains in Colorado (then part of the western Kansas Territory) brought on a gold rush and a consequent flood of white immigration across Cheyenne and Arapaho lands.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Colorado territorial officials pressured federal authorities to redefine and reduce the extent of Indian treaty lands.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In the summer of 1858, during the Pike's Peak Gold Rush, a group of gold prospectors from Lawrence, Kansas, established Montana City as a mining town on the banks of the South Platte River in what was then western Kansas Territory, on traditional lands of Cheyenne and Arapaho.
[src:denver/denver-p01] This was the first historical settlement in what later became the city of Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] But the site faded quickly, and by the summer of 1859 it was abandoned in favor of Auraria (named after the gold-mining town of Auraria, Georgia) and St.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Larimer named the townsite Denver City to curry favor with Kansas Territorial Governor James W.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Larimer hoped the town's name would help it be selected as the county seat of Arapahoe County, but unbeknownst to him, Governor Denver had already resigned from office.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The location was accessible to existing trails and was across the South Platte River from the site of seasonal encampments of the Cheyenne and Arapaho.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The site of these first towns is now occupied by Confluence Park near downtown Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Wynkoop came to Colorado in 1859 and became one of the city's founders.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Wynkoop Street in Denver is named after him.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Larimer, along with associates in the St.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Charles City Land Company, sold parcels in the town to merchants and miners, with the intention of creating a major city that would cater to new immigrants.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver City was a frontier town, with an economy based on servicing local miners with gambling, saloons, livestock, and goods trading.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In the early years, land parcels were often traded for grubstakes or gambled away by miners in Auraria.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In May 1859, Denver City residents donated 53 lots to the Leavenworth & Pike's Peak Express in order to secure the region's first overland wagon route.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Offering daily service for "passengers, mail, freight, and gold", the Express reached Denver on a trail that trimmed westward travel time from twelve days to six.
[src:denver/denver-p01] On February 18, 1861, six chiefs of the Southern Cheyenne and four of the Arapaho signed the Treaty of Fort Wise with the United States at Bent's New Fort at Big Timbers near what is now Lamar, Colorado.
[src:denver/denver-p01] They ceded more than 90 percent of the lands designated for them by the Fort Laramie Treaty, including the area of modern Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Some Cheyennes opposed to the treaty, saying that it had been signed by a small minority of the chiefs without the consent or approval of the rest of the tribe, that the signatories had not understood what they signed, and that they had been bribed to sign by a large distribution of gifts.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The territorial government of Colorado, however, claimed the treaty was a "solemn obligation" and considered that those Indians who refused to abide by it were hostile and planning a war.
[src:denver/denver-p01] On February 28, 1861, the Colorado Territory was created, Arapahoe County was formed on November 1, 1861, and Denver City was incorporated on November 7, 1861.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver City served as the Arapahoe County Seat from 1861 until consolidation in 1902.
[src:denver/denver-p01] With its newfound importance, Denver City shortened its name to Denver in 1866.
[src:denver/denver-p01] On December 9, 1867, Denver became the territorial capital.
[src:denver/denver-p01] On August 1, 1876, Colorado was admitted to the Union.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver was made the permanent state capital in a 1881 Colorado state capital referendum.
[src:denver/denver-p01] This disagreement on the validity of Treaty of Fort Wise escalated to bring about the Colorado War of 1864 and 1865, during which the brutal Sand Creek massacre against Cheyenne and Arapaho peoples occurred.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The aftermath of the war was the dissolution of the reservation in Eastern Colorado, the signing of Medicine Lodge Treaty which stipulated that the Cheyenne and Arapaho peoples would be relocated outside of their traditional territory.
[src:denver/denver-p01] This treaty term was achieved, even though the treaty was not legally ratified by the tribal members, as per the treaty's own terms.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Thus, by the end of 1860s, this effectively and completely cleared the Denver area of its indigenous inhabitants.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Although by the close of the 1860s Denver residents could look with pride at their success establishing a vibrant supply and service center, the decision to route the nation's first transcontinental railroad through Cheyenne City, rather than Denver, threatened the prosperity of the young town.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The transcontinental railroad passed a daunting 100 miles (160 kilometers) away, but citizens mobilized to build a railroad to connect Denver to it.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Spearheaded by visionary leaders, including Territorial Governor John Evans, David Moffat, and Walter Cheesman, fundraising began.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Within three days, $300,000 had been raised, and citizens were optimistic.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Fundraising stalled before enough was raised, forcing these visionary leaders to take control of the debt-ridden railroad.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Despite challenges, on June 24, 1870, citizens cheered as the Denver Pacific completed the link to the transcontinental railroad, ushering in a new age of prosperity for Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Finally linked to the rest of the nation by rail, Denver prospered as a service and supply center.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The young city grew during these years, attracting millionaires with their mansions, as well as a mixture of crime and poverty of a rapidly growing city.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver citizens were proud when the rich chose Denver and were thrilled when Horace Tabor, the Leadville mining millionaire, built a business block at 16th and Larimer, as well as the elegant Tabor Grand Opera House.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Luxurious hotels, including the much-loved Brown Palace Hotel, soon followed, as well as splendid homes for millionaires, such as the Croke, Patterson, Campbell Mansion at 11th and Pennsylvania and the now-demolished Moffat Mansion at 8th and Grant.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Intent on transforming Denver into one of the world's great cities, leaders wooed industry and attracted laborers to work in these factories.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Soon, in addition to the elite and a large middle class, Denver had a growing population of immigrant German, Italian, and Chinese laborers, soon followed by African Americans from the Deep South and Hispanic workers.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The influx of the new residents strained available housing.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In addition, the Silver Crash of 1893 unsettled political, social, and economic balances.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Competition among the different ethnic groups was often expressed as bigotry, and social tensions gave rise to the Red Scare.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Americans were suspicious of immigrants, who were sometimes allied with socialist and labor union causes.
[src:denver/denver-p01] After World War I, a revival of the Ku Klux Klan attracted white, native-born Americans who were anxious about the many changes in society.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Unlike the earlier organization that was active in the rural South, KKK chapters developed in urban areas of the Midwest and West, including Denver, and into Idaho and Oregon.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Corruption and crime also developed in Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Between the years 1880 and 1895, the city underwent a huge rise in corruption, as crime bosses, such as Soapy Smith, worked side by side with elected officials and the police to control elections, gambling, and bunco gangs.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The city also suffered a depression in 1893 after the crash of silver prices.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In 1887, the precursor to the international charity United Way was formed in Denver by local religious leaders, who raised funds and coordinated various charities to help Denver's poor.
[src:denver/denver-p01] By 1890, Denver had grown to be the second-largest city west of Omaha, Nebraska.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In 1900, whites represented 96.8% of Denver's population.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The African American and Hispanic populations increased with migrations of the 20th century.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Many African Americans first came as workers on the railroad, which had a terminus in Denver, and began to settle there.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Between the 1880s and 1930s, Denver's floriculture industry developed and thrived.
[src:denver/denver-p01] This period became known locally as the Carnation Gold Rush.
[src:denver/denver-p01] A bill proposing a state constitutional amendment to allow home rule for Denver and other municipalities was introduced in the legislature in 1901, and passed.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The measure called for a statewide referendum, which voters approved in 1902.
[src:denver/denver-p01] On December 1 that year, Governor James Orman proclaimed the amendment part of the state's fundamental law.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The City and County of Denver came into being on that date and was separated from Arapahoe and Adams counties.
[src:denver/denver-p01] From 1953 to 1989, the Rocky Flats Plant, a DOE nuclear weapon facility that was about 15 miles from Denver, produced fissile plutonium "pits" for nuclear warheads.
[src:denver/denver-p01] A major fire at the facility in 1957, as well as leakage from nuclear waste stored at the site between 1958 and 1968, resulted in the contamination of some parts of Denver, to varying degrees, with plutonium-239, a harmful radioactive substance with a half-life of 24,200 years.
[src:denver/denver-p01] A 1981 study by the Jefferson County health director, Carl Johnson, linked the contamination to an increase in birth defects and cancer incidence in central Denver and nearer Rocky Flats.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Later studies confirmed many of his findings.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Plutonium contamination was still present outside the former plant site as of August 2010.
[src:denver/denver-p01] It presents risks to building the envisioned Jefferson Parkway, which would complete Denver's automotive beltway.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In 1970, Denver was selected to host the 1976 Winter Olympics to coincide with Colorado's centennial celebration, but in November 1972, Colorado voters rejected ballot initiatives allocating public funds for the games, and the games moved to Innsbruck, Austria.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The notoriety of being the only city ever to decline to host an Olympiad after being selected has made subsequent bids difficult.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The movement against hosting the games was based largely on environmental issues and was led by State Representative Richard Lamm.
[src:denver/denver-p01] He was subsequently elected to three terms (1975–87) as Colorado governor.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver explored a potential bid for the 2022 Winter Olympics, but no bid was submitted.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In 2010, Denver adopted a comprehensive update of its zoning code, which was developed to guide development as envisioned in adopted plans such as Blueprint Denver, Transit Oriented Development Strategic Plan, Greenprint Denver, and the Strategic Transportation Plan.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver has hosted the Democratic National Convention twice, in 1908 and 2008.
[src:denver/denver-p01] It promoted the city on the national, political, and socioeconomic stage.
[src:denver/denver-p01] On August 10–15, 1993, Denver hosted the Catholic Church's 6th World Youth Day, which was attended by an estimated 500,000, making it the largest gathering in Colorado history.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In 2015, a new commuter railway system commenced operations in the Denver metropolitan area with a network operation of 25 kV 60 Hz.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver has been known historically as the *Queen City of the Plains* and the *Queen City of the West*, because of its important role in the agricultural industry of the High Plains region in eastern Colorado and along the foothills of the Colorado Front Range.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Evans) can be seen to the left beyond the city skyline.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver is in the center of the Front Range Urban Corridor, between the Rocky Mountains to the west and the High Plains to the east.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Its topography consists of plains in the city center with hilly areas to the north, west, and south.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The city's downtown district is about 12 mi (19 km) east of the foothills of the Rockies.
[src:denver/denver-p01] It is the only state capital in the United States that is a consolidated city-county.
[src:denver/denver-p01] At the 2020 United States census, the City and County of Denver had an area of 99,025 acres (400.739 km2), including 1,057 acres (4.276 km2) of water.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The City and County of Denver is surrounded by three other counties: Adams County to the north and east, Arapahoe County to the south and east, and Jefferson County to the west.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver's nickname is the "Mile-High City", as its official elevation is one mile (5,280 ft; 1,609 m) above sea level, defined by the elevation of the spot of a benchmark on the steps of the State Capitol building.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The elevation of the entire city ranges from 5,130 to 5,690 feet (1,560 to 1,730 m).
[src:denver/denver-p01] The City and County of Denver has 78 official neighborhoods used for planning and administration.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The system of neighborhood boundaries and names dates to 1970 when city planners divided the city into 73 groups of one to four census tracts, called "statistical neighborhoods", most of which are unchanged since then.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Unlike some other cities, such as Chicago, Denver does not have official larger area designations.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Colloquially, names such as Northside and Westside are still in use, but not well-known.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Community planners have recently been using a set of 19 larger areas, all of which are groups of statistical neighborhoods, as part of the Area Planning process.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver also has a number of colloquial neighborhood names and boundaries reflecting how people in an area, or others such as community groups and real estate developers, have defined areas.
[src:denver/denver-p01] One of Denver's newer neighborhoods was built on the site of Stapleton International Airport, named after former Denver mayor Benjamin F.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Stapleton, a member of the Ku Klux Klan.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In 2020, the neighborhood's community association voted to change the name from Stapleton to Central Park (see more in Politics section below).
[src:denver/denver-p01] The Central Park neighborhood itself has 12 "neighborhoods" within its boundaries.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver features a cool semi-arid climate (Köppen climate classification: *BSk*, Trewartha: *BSao*) with generally low humidity and around 3,100 hours of sunshine per year, although humid microclimates can be found nearby depending on exact location.
[src:denver/denver-p01] These humid microclimates have the temperature of a hot-summer humid continental climate (Koppen: *Dfa*) or a humid subtropical climate (Koppen: *Cfa*) when using the 27 °F (−3 °C) isotherm.
[src:denver/denver-p01] It has four distinct seasons and receives most of its precipitation from April through August.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Due to its inland location on the High Plains, at the foot of the Rocky Mountains, the region can be subject to sudden changes in weather.
[src:denver/denver-p01] July is the warmest month, with an average high temperature of 89.9 °F (32.2 °C).
[src:denver/denver-p01] Summers range from warm to hot with occasional, sometimes severe, afternoon thunderstorms and high temperatures reaching 90 °F (32 °C) on 38 days annually, and occasionally 100 °F (38 °C).
[src:denver/denver-p01] December, the coldest month of the year, has an average daily high temperature of 44 °F (6.7 °C).
[src:denver/denver-p01] Winters consist of periods of snow and very low temperatures alternating with periods of milder weather due to the warming effect of Chinook winds.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In winter, daytime highs occasionally exceed 60 °F (16 °C), but they also often fail to reach 32 °F (0 °C) during periods of cold weather.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Occasionally, daytime highs can even fail to rise above 0 °F (−18 °C) due to arctic air masses.
[src:denver/denver-p01] On the coldest nights of the year, lows can fall to −10 °F (−23 °C) or below, with the city experiencing a low of −24 °F (−31 °C) on December 22, 2022, with a wind chill of −40 °F (−40 °C).
[src:denver/denver-p01] Snowfall is common throughout the late fall, winter and early spring, averaging 53.5 inches (136 cm) for 1981–2010; but in the 2021 winter season, Denver began the month of December without any snowfall for the first time in history.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The average window for measurable (≥0.1 in or 0.25 cm) snow is October 17 through April 27; however, measurable snowfall has occurred as early as September 4 and as late as June 3.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Due to the city's high elevation and aridity, diurnal temperature variation is large throughout the year.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Tornadoes are rare west of the I-25 corridor; one notable exception was an F3 tornado that struck 4.4 miles (7.1 km) south of downtown on June 15, 1988.
[src:denver/denver-p01] On the other hand, the suburbs east of Denver and the city's east-northeastern extension (Denver International Airport) can see a few tornadoes, often weak landspout tornadoes, each spring and summer, especially during June, with the enhancement of the Denver Convergence Vorticity Zone (DCVZ).
[src:denver/denver-p01] The DCVZ, also known as the Denver Cyclone, is a variable vortex of storm-forming air flow usually found north and east of downtown, and which often includes the airport.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Heavy weather from the DCVZ can disrupt airport operations.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In a study looking at hail events in areas with a population of at least 50,000, Denver was found to be ranked 10th most prone to hail storms in the continental United States.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In fact, Denver has had three of the top 10 costliest hailstorms in U.S. history, on July 11, 1990; July 20, 2009; and May 8, 2017.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Based on 30-year averages obtained from NOAA's National Climatic Data Center for the months of December, January and February, Weather Channel ranked Denver the 18th-coldest major U.S. city as of 2014.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver's official weather station is at Denver International Airport, roughly 20 miles (32 km) from downtown.
[src:denver/denver-p01] A 2019 analysis showed the average temperature at Denver International Airport, 50.2 °F (10 °C), was significantly cooler than downtown, 53.0 °F (12 °C).
[src:denver/denver-p01] Many of the suburbs also have warmer temperatures and there is controversy regarding the location of the official temperature readings.
[src:denver/denver-p01] As of the 2020 census, the population of the City and County of Denver was 715,522, making it the 19th most populous U.S. city.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver is the most populous city within a radius centered in the city and of 550-mile (890 km) magnitude.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denverites is a term used for residents of Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] According to the 2020 census, the City and County of Denver contained 715,522 people and 301,501 households.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The population density was 3,922.6 inhabitants per square mile (1,514.5 inhabitants/km2) including the airport.
[src:denver/denver-p01] There were 338,341 housing units at an average density of 1,751 units per square mile (676 units/km2).
[src:denver/denver-p01] However, the average density throughout most Denver neighborhoods tends to be higher.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Without the 80249 zip code (47.3 sq mi, 8,407 residents) near the airport, the average density increases to around 5,470 per square mile.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Approximately 70.3% of the population (over five years old) spoke only English at home.
[src:denver/denver-p01] An additional 23.5% of the population spoke Spanish at home.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In terms of ancestry, 31.8% were Hispanic or Latino, 14.6% of the population were of German ancestry, 9.7% were of Irish ancestry, 8.9% were of English ancestry, and 4.0% were of Italian ancestry.
[src:denver/denver-p01] There were 250,906 households, of which 23.2% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 34.7% were married couples living together, 10.8% had a female householder with no husband present, and 50.1% were non-families.
[src:denver/denver-p01] 39.3% of all households were made up of individuals, and 9.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The average household size was 2.27, and the average family size was 3.14.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Overall there were 102.1 males for every 100 females.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Due to a skewed sex ratio wherein single men outnumber single women, some protologists had nicknamed the city as *Menver*.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The median household income was $45,438, and the median family income was $48,195.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Males had a median income of $36,232 versus $33,768 for females.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The per capita income for the city was $24,101.
[src:denver/denver-p01] 19.1% of the population and 14.6% of families were below the poverty line.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Out of the total population, 25.3% of those under the age of 18 and 13.7% of those 65 and older were living below the poverty line.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver has one of the largest populations of Mexican-Americans in the entire United States.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Approximately one third of the city is Hispanic, with the overwhelming majority of them being of Mexican descent.
[src:denver/denver-p01] English, German, Irish, Swedish, Italian, Polish, Chinese, Japanese, Greek, and Russian immigrants immigrated to Denver by the 1920s.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In total, 27.72% (148,335) of Denver's population aged five and older spoke a language other than English.
[src:denver/denver-p01] According to a report in the *Journal of the American Medical Association*, residents of Denver had a 2014 life expectancy of 80.02 years.
[src:denver/denver-p01] According to the Pew Research Center 53% of adults in the Denver Metro area identified as Christians in 2023-24.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The most common denomination were Catholics (17%), followed by Mainline Protestants (15%) and Evangelical Protestants (10%).
[src:denver/denver-p01] A total of 39% were not religiously affiliated.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The mother church of the Catholic Archdiocese of Denver is the Cathedral Basilica of the Immaculate Conception in Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] It is the seat of the Archbishop of Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The Denver MSA had a gross metropolitan product of $311.9 billion in 2023, making it the 18th largest metro economy in the United States.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Additionally, the 12-County Denver–Aurora, CO Combined Statistical Area had a GDP of $377.7 billion in 2023 while the broader Front Range had a GDP of $474.6 billion.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver's economy is based partially on its geographic position and its connection to some of the country's major transportation systems.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Because Denver is the largest city within 500 miles (800 km), it has become a natural location for storage and distribution of goods and services to the Mountain States, Southwest states, as well as all western states.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Another benefit for distribution is that Denver is nearly equidistant from large cities of the Midwest, such as Chicago and St.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Louis and some large cities of the West Coast, such as Los Angeles and San Francisco.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Over the years, the city has been home to other large corporations in the central United States, making Denver a key trade point for the country.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Several well-known companies originated in or have relocated to Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] William Ainsworth opened the Denver Instrument Company in 1895 to make analytical balances for gold assayers.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Samsonite began in Denver in 1910 as Shwayder Trunk Manufacturing Company, but Samsonite closed its NE Denver factory in 2001, and moved its headquarters to Massachusetts after a change of ownership in 2006.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Qwest Corporation, founded in Denver in 1911 as Mountain States Telephone & Telegraph Company, is now a part of Lumen Technologies (previously CenturyLink).
[src:denver/denver-p01] On October 31, 1937, Continental Airlines, now United Airlines, moved its headquarters to Stapleton Airport in Denver, Colorado (before United Airlines later moved to its current home in Chicago).
[src:denver/denver-p01] Six arranged to have the headquarters moved to Denver from El Paso, Texas because Six believed that the airline should have its headquarters in a large city with a potential base of customers.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Continental later moved to Houston from Denver, but merged with United Airlines in 2013.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Throughout that time, the company held a large employee base in the Denver area, which is home to the United Airlines Flight Training Center in the Central Park neighborhood.
[src:denver/denver-p01] MediaNews Group purchased the *Denver Post* in 1987; the company is based in Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The Gates Corporation, the world's largest producer of automotive belts and hoses, was established in S.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Russell Stover Candies made its first chocolate candy in Denver in 1923, but moved to Kansas City in 1969.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The original Frontier Airlines began operations at Denver's old Stapleton International Airport in 1950; Frontier was reincarnated at DIA in 1994.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Scott's Liquid Gold, Inc., has been making furniture polish in Denver since 1954.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Village Inn restaurants began as a single pancake house in Denver in 1958.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Big O Tires, LLC, of Centennial opened its first franchise in 1962 in Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The Shane Company sold its first diamond jewelry in 1971 in Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In 1973 Re/Max made Denver its headquarters.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Johns Manville Corp., a manufacturer of insulation and roofing products, relocated its headquarters to Denver from New York in 1972.
[src:denver/denver-p01] CH2M Hill, an engineering and construction firm, relocated from Oregon to the Denver Technological Center in 1980.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The Ball Corporation sold its glass business in Indiana in the 1990s and moved to suburban Broomfield; Ball has several operations in greater Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Molson Coors Brewing Company established its U.S. headquarters in Denver in 2005, but announced its departure in 2019.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Its subsidiary and regional wholesale distributor, Coors Distributing Company, is in NW Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The Newmont Mining Corporation, the second-largest gold producer in North America and one of the largest in the world, is headquartered in Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] MapQuest, an online site for maps, directions and business listings, is headquartered in Denver's LoDo district.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Large Denver-area employers that have headquarters elsewhere include Lockheed Martin Corp., United Airlines, Kroger Co. and Xcel Energy, Inc.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Geography also allows Denver to have a considerable government presence, with many federal agencies based or having offices in the Denver area.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Along with federal agencies come many companies based on US defense and space projects, and more jobs are brought to the city by virtue of its being the capital of the state of Colorado.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The Denver area is home to the former nuclear weapons plant Rocky Flats, the Denver Federal Center, Byron G.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Rogers Federal Building and United States Courthouse, the Denver Mint, and the National Renewable Energy Laboratory.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In 2005, a $310.7 million expansion of the Colorado Convention Center was completed, doubling its size.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The hope was the center's expansion would elevate the city to one of the top 10 cities in the nation for holding a convention.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver's position near the mineral-rich Rocky Mountains encouraged mining and energy companies to spring up in the area.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In the early days of the city, gold and silver booms and busts played a large role in the city's economic success.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In the 1970s and early 1980s, the energy crisis in America and resulting high oil prices created an energy boom in Denver captured in the soap opera *Dynasty*.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver was built up considerably during this time with the construction of many new downtown skyscrapers.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The industry has recovered and the region has 700 employed petroleum engineers.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Advances in hydraulic fracturing have made the DJ Basin of Colorado into an accessible and lucrative oil play.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Energy and mining are still important in Denver's economy today, with companies such as Ovintiv, Halliburton, Smith International, Rio Tinto Group, Newmont Mining, and Chevron Corporation, headquartered or having significant operations.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver's west-central geographic location in the Mountain Time Zone (UTC−7) also benefits the telecommunications industry by allowing communication with both North American coasts, South America, Europe, and Asia on the same business day.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver's location on the 105th meridian at over one mile (1.6 km) in elevation also enables it to be the largest city in the U.S. to offer a "one-bounce" real-time satellite uplink to six continents in the same business day.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Qwest Communications now part of CenturyLink, Dish Network Corporation, Starz, DIRECTV, and Comcast are a few of the many telecommunications companies with operations in the Denver area.
[src:denver/denver-p01] These and other high-tech companies had a boom in Denver in the mid to late 1990s.
[src:denver/denver-p01] After a rise in unemployment in the Great Recession, Denver's unemployment rate recovered and had one of the lowest unemployment rates in the nation at 2.6% in November 2016.
[src:denver/denver-p01] As of December 2016, the unemployment rate for the Denver–Aurora–Broomfield MSA is 2.6%.
[src:denver/denver-p01] The Downtown region has seen increased real estate investment with the construction of several new skyscrapers from 2010 onward and major development around Denver Union Station.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Denver has also enjoyed success as a pioneer in the fast-casual restaurant industry, with many popular national chain restaurants founded and based in Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Quiznos and Smashburger were founded and headquartered in Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Qdoba Mexican Grill, Noodles & Company, and Good Times Burgers & Frozen Custard originated in Denver, but have moved their headquarters to the suburbs of Wheat Ridge, Broomfield, and Golden, respectively.
[src:denver/denver-p01] Chipotle Mexican Grill was founded in Denver, but moved its headquarters to Newport Beach, California in 2018.
[src:denver/denver-p01] In 2024, Denver based Ibotta's initial public offering (IPO) was the largest tech IPO in Colorado's history.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Apollo Hall opened soon after the city's founding in 1859 and staged many plays for eager settlers.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In the 1880s Horace Tabor built Denver's first opera house.
[src:denver/denver-p02] After the start of the 20th century, city leaders embarked on a city beautification program that created many of the city's parks, parkways, museums, and the Municipal Auditorium, which was home to the 1908 Democratic National Convention and is now known as the Ellie Caulkins Opera House.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver and the metropolitan areas around it continued to support culture.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In July 1982, Denver hosted the World Theatre Festival at the Denver Center for Performing Arts, which comprised a program of 114 performances of 18 plays, by theatre companies from 13 countries, across 25 days.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In 1988, voters in the Denver Metropolitan Area approved the Scientific and Cultural Facilities Tax (commonly known as SCFD), a 0.1% (1 cent per $10) sales tax that contributes money to various cultural and scientific facilities and organizations throughout the Metro area.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The tax was renewed by voters in 1994 and 2004 and allowed the SCFD to operate until 2018.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Ballot issue 4B in 2016 won approval 62.8 percent to 37.2 percent, by Denver metro area voters, to extend the SCFD sales tax until 2030.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver is home to a wide array of museums.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Many are nationally recognized, including a new wing for the Denver Art Museum by architect Daniel Libeskind, the nation's second-largest Performing Arts Center after Lincoln Center in New York City, and bustling neighborhoods such as LoDo, filled with art galleries, restaurants, bars and clubs.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Its neighborhoods also continue their influx of diverse people and businesses while the city's cultural institutions grow and prosper.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The city acquired the estate of abstract expressionist painter Clyfford Still in 2004 and built a museum to exhibit his works near the Denver Art Museum.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Denver Museum of Nature and Science holds an aquamarine specimen valued at over $1 million, as well as specimens of the state mineral, rhodochrosite.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Every September the Denver Mart, at 451 E.
[src:denver/denver-p02] 58th Avenue, hosts a gem and mineral show.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The state history museum, History Colorado Center, opened in April 2012.
[src:denver/denver-p02] It features hands-on and interactive exhibits, artifacts and programs about Colorado history.
[src:denver/denver-p02] It was named in 2013 by *True West Magazine* as one of the top-ten "must see" history museums in the country.
[src:denver/denver-p02] History Colorado's Byers-Evans House Museum and the Molly Brown House are nearby.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver has numerous art districts, including Denver's Art District on Santa Fe and the River North Art District (RiNo).
[src:denver/denver-p02] While Denver may not be as recognized for historical musical prominence as some other American cities, it has an active pop, jazz, jam, folk, metal, and classical music scene, which has nurtured several artists and genres to regional, national, and even international attention.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Of particular note is Denver's importance in the folk scene of the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Well-known folk artists such as Bob Dylan, Judy Collins and John Denver lived in Denver at various points during this time and performed at local clubs.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Three members of the widely popular group Earth, Wind, and Fire are also from Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p02] More recent Denver-based artists include India Arie, Nathaniel Rateliff & the Night Sweats, The Lumineers, Air Dubai, The Fray, Flobots, Cephalic Carnage, Axe Murder Boyz, Deuce Mob, Havok, Bloodstrike, Primitive Man, and Five Iron Frenzy.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver is also home to the Denver Record Collectors Expo, a biannual music collectors event.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Because of its proximity to the mountains and generally sunny weather, Denver has gained a reputation as being a very active, outdoor-oriented city.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Many Denver residents spend the weekends in the mountains; skiing in the winter and hiking, climbing, kayaking, and camping in the summer.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver and surrounding cities are home to a large number of local and national breweries.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Many of the region's restaurants have on-site breweries, and some larger brewers offer tours, including Coors and New Belgium Brewing Company.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The city also welcomes visitors from around the world when it hosts the annual Great American Beer Festival each fall.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver used to be a major trading center for beef and livestock when ranchers would drive (or later transport) cattle to the Denver Union Stockyards for sale.
[src:denver/denver-p02] As a celebration of that history, for more than a century Denver has hosted the annual National Western Stock Show, attracting as many as 10,000 animals and 700,000 attendees.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The show is held every January at the National Western Complex northeast of downtown.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver is known for its dedication to New Mexican cuisine and the Chile.
[src:denver/denver-p02] It is best known for its green and red chile sauce, Colorado burrito, Southwest (Denver) omelette, breakfast burrito, empanadas, chiles rellenos, and tamales.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver is also known for other types of food such as Rocky Mountain oysters, rainbow trout, and the Denver sandwich.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Dragon Boat Festival in July, Moon Festival in September and Chinese New Year are annual events in Denver for the Chinese and Asian-American communities.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Chinese hot pot (huo guo) and Korean BBQ restaurants have been growing in popularity.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Denver area has two Chinese newspapers, the *Chinese American Post* and the *Colorado Chinese News*.
[src:denver/denver-p02] A Korean Newspaper, the "Colorado Times News" is also based in Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver has long been a place tolerant of the LGBTQ (lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, and queer) community.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Many gay bars can be found on Colfax Avenue and on South Broadway.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Every June, Denver hosts the annual Denver PrideFest in Civic Center Park, the largest LGBTQ Pride festival in the Rocky Mountain region.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver is the setting for *The Bill Engvall Show*, Tim Allen's *Last Man Standing,* and the 18th season of MTV's *The Real World*.
[src:denver/denver-p02] It was also the setting for the prime time drama *Dynasty* from 1981 to 1989 (although the show was mostly filmed in Los Angeles).
[src:denver/denver-p02] From 1998 to 2002 the city's Alameda East Veterinary Hospital was home to the Animal Planet series *Emergency Vets*, which spun off three documentary specials and the current Animal Planet series *E-Vet Interns*.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The city is also the setting for the Disney Channel sitcom *Good Luck Charlie*.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver is home to a variety of sports teams and is one of 12 U.S. cities with teams from four major league sports (the Denver metro area is the smallest metropolitan area in the country to have a team in all four major sports leagues).
[src:denver/denver-p02] Including Major League Soccer, it is also one of 10 U.S. cities to have five major sports teams.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Denver Broncos of the National Football League have drawn crowds of over 70,000 since their origins in the early 1960s, and continue to draw fans today to their current home Empower Field at Mile High.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Broncos have sold out every home game (except for strike-replacement games) since 1970.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Broncos have advanced to eight Super Bowls and won back-to-back titles in 1997 and 1998, and won again in 2015.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Colorado Rockies were created as an expansion franchise in 1993 and Coors Field opened in 1995.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Rockies advanced to the playoffs that year but were eliminated in the first round.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In 2007, they advanced to the playoffs as a wild-card entrant, won the NL Championship Series, and brought the World Series to Denver for the first time but were swept in four games by the Boston Red Sox.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver has been home to two National Hockey League teams.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Colorado Rockies played from 1976 to 1982, but later moved to the New York metropolitan area to become the New Jersey Devils.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Colorado Avalanche joined in 1995, after relocating from Quebec City.
[src:denver/denver-p02] While in Denver, they have won three Stanley Cups in 1996, 2001, and 2022.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Denver Nuggets joined the American Basketball Association in 1967 and the National Basketball Association in 1976.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Nuggets won their first NBA championship in 2023.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Avalanche and Nuggets have both played at Ball Arena (formerly known as Pepsi Center) since 1999.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Major League Soccer team Colorado Rapids play in Dick's Sporting Goods Park, an 18,000-seat soccer-specific stadium opened for the 2007 MLS season in the Denver suburb of Commerce City.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver has several additional professional teams.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In 2006, Denver established a Major League Lacrosse team, the Denver Outlaws.
[src:denver/denver-p02] They play in Empower Field at Mile High.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In 2006, the Denver Outlaws won the Western Conference Championship and then won their first championship in 2014 eight years later.
[src:denver/denver-p02] They also won in 2016 and 2018 and would fold in 2020 with the MLL-PLL merger.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Colorado Mammoth of the National Lacrosse League play at Ball Arena.
[src:denver/denver-p02] They won championships in 2006 and 2022.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In 2018, the Denver Bandits were established as the first professional football team for women in Colorado and will be a part of the initial season for the Women's National Football Conference (WNFC) in 2019.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver was awarded a National Women's Soccer League team called Denver Summit FC in 2025.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver submitted the winning bid to host the 1976 Winter Olympics but subsequently withdrew in 1972 due to environmental concerns and Colorado voters blocking using public funds to pay for the games.
[src:denver/denver-p02] This gives Denver the distinction of being the first (and currently only) city to back out after having won its bid to host the Olympics.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver and Colorado Springs hosted the 1962 World Ice Hockey Championships.
[src:denver/denver-p02] As of 2006, Denver had over 200 parks, from small pocket parks all over the city to the giant 314-acre (1.27 km2) City Park.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver also has 29 recreation centers providing places and programming for resident's recreation and relaxation.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Many of Denver's parks were acquired from state lands in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:denver/denver-p02] This coincided with the City Beautiful movement, and Denver mayor Robert Speer (1904–12 and 1916–18) set out to expand and beautify the city's parks.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Reinhard Schuetze was the city's first landscape architect, and he brought his German-educated landscaping genius to Washington Park, Cheesman Park, and City Park among others.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Speer used Schuetze as well as other landscape architects such as Frederick Law Olmsted Jr. and Saco Rienk DeBoer to design not only parks such as Civic Center Park, but many city parkways and tree-lawns.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Cheesman Park neighbor the Denver Botanic Gardens displays the beauty and versatility of micro-climates within the semi-arid Denver Basin.
[src:denver/denver-p02] All of these parks were fed with South Platte River water diverted through the city ditch.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In addition to the parks within Denver, the city acquired land for mountain parks starting in the 1911s.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Over the years, Denver has acquired, built and maintained approximately 14,000 acres (57 km2) of mountain parks, including Red Rocks Park, which is known for its scenery and musical history revolving around the unique Red Rocks Amphitheatre.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver also owns the mountain on which the Winter Park Resort ski area operates in Grand County, 67 miles (110 km) west of Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p02] City parks are important places for Denverites and visitors, inciting controversy with every change.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver continues to grow its park system with the development of many new parks along the Platte River through the city, and with Central Park and Bluff Lake Nature Center in the Central Park neighborhood redevelopment.
[src:denver/denver-p02] All of these parks are important gathering places for residents and allow what was once a dry plain to be lush, active, and green.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver is also home to a large network of public community gardens, most of which are managed by Denver Urban Gardens, a non-profit organization.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Since 1974, Denver and the surrounding jurisdictions have rehabilitated the urban South Platte River and its tributaries for recreational use by hikers and cyclists.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The main stem of the South Platte River Greenway runs along the South Platte 35 miles (56 km) into Adams County in the north.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Greenway project is recognized as one of the best urban reclamation projects in the U.S., winning, for example, the Silver Medal Rudy Bruner Award for Urban Excellence in 2001.
[src:denver/denver-p02] As of 2022, Park Score by the Trust for Public Land, a national land conservation organization, reported Denver as having the 18th best park system among the 50 most populous U.S. cities.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The report noted that 89% of Denverites live within a 10-minute walk of a park.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver is a consolidated city-county with a mayor elected on a nonpartisan ballot, a 13-member city council, and an auditor.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Denver City Council is elected from 11 districts with two at-large council members and is responsible for passing and changing all laws, resolutions, and ordinances, usually after a public hearing.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The city council can also call for misconduct investigations of Denver's departmental officials.
[src:denver/denver-p02] All elected officials have four-year terms, with a maximum of three terms.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver has a strong mayor/weak city council government.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The mayor can approve or veto any ordinances or resolutions approved by the council, makes sure all contracts with the city are kept and performed, signs all bonds and contracts, is responsible for the city budget, and can appoint people to various city departments, organizations, and commissions.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The council can override the mayor's veto with a nine votes.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The city budget must be approved and can be changed by a simple majority vote of the council.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The auditor checks all expenditures and may refuse to allow specific ones, usually for financial reasons.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Denver Department of Safety oversees three branches: the Denver Police Department, Denver Fire Department, and Denver Sheriff Department.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Denver County Court is an integrated Colorado County Court and Municipal Court and is managed by Denver instead of the state.
[src:denver/denver-p02] While Denver elections are nonpartisan, Democrats have long dominated the city's politics; most citywide officials are known to be registered with the Democratic Party.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The mayor's office has been occupied by a Democrat since the 1963 municipal election.
[src:denver/denver-p02] All the city's seats in the state legislature are held by Democrats.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In statewide elections, the city also tends to favor Democrats, though Republicans were occasionally competitive until the turn of the millennium.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The last Republican to win Denver in a gubernatorial election was John A.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Bill Owens in 2002 remains the last Republican governor to receive at least 40% of Denver's vote.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The last Republican Senator to carry Denver was William L.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The last statewide Republican officeholder to carry Denver was Secretary of State Victoria Buckley in 1994 by 1.2% margin; she was, at the time, the highest ranking African-American Republican woman in the United States.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In federal elections, Denver is a Democratic stronghold.
[src:denver/denver-p02] It has supported a Democrat for president in every election since 1984.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Despite then-president Ronald Reagan's landslide that year both nationally and in Colorado, Democrat Walter Mondale won Denver by a margin of 2.32%, and since then the party has increased its margin in almost every election.
[src:denver/denver-p02] At the federal level, Denver is the heart of Colorado's 1st congressional district, which includes all of Denver and parts of Arapahoe County.
[src:denver/denver-p02] It is the most Democratic district in the Mountain West and has been in Democratic hands for all but two terms since 1933.
[src:denver/denver-p02] It is currently represented by Democrat Diana DeGette.
[src:denver/denver-p02] A portion of southeast Denver, roughly half of the Indian Creek neighborhood and a small part of the Virginia Village neighborhood, is in Colorado's 6th congressional district, represented by Democrat Jason Crow.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Stapleton was the mayor of Denver for two periods, from 1923 to 1931 and from 1935 to 1947.
[src:denver/denver-p02] He was responsible for many civic improvements, notably during his second term, when he had access to funds and manpower from the New Deal.
[src:denver/denver-p02] During this time, the park system was considerably expanded and the Civic Center completed.
[src:denver/denver-p02] His signature project was the construction of Denver Municipal Airport, which began in 1929 amid heavy criticism.
[src:denver/denver-p02] It was later renamed Stapleton International Airport in his honor.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Today, the airport has been replaced by a neighborhood initially named Stapleton.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In 2020, during the George Floyd protests, because of Stapleton's demonstrated racism and prominent membership in the Ku Klux Klan, neighborhood residents changed the name to Central Park.
[src:denver/denver-p02] During the 1960s and 1970s, Denver was one of the centers of the Chicano Movement.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The boxer-turned-activist Rodolfo "Corky" Gonzales formed an organization called the Crusade for Justice, which battled police brutality, fought for bilingual education, and, most notably, hosted the First National Chicano Youth Liberation Conference in March 1969.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In recent years, Denver has taken a stance on helping people who are or become homeless, particularly under the administrations of mayors John Hickenlooper and Wellington Webb.
[src:denver/denver-p02] At a rate of 19 homeless per 10,000 residents in 2011 as compared to 50 or more per 10,000 residents for the four metro areas with the highest rate of homelessness, Denver's homeless population and rate of homeless are both considerably lower than many other major cities.
[src:denver/denver-p02] But residents of the city streets suffer Denver winters – which, although mild and dry much of the time, can have brief periods of extremely cold temperatures and snow.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In 2005, Denver became the first major U.S. city to vote to make the private possession of less than an ounce of marijuana legal for adults 21 and older.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver passed an initiative in the fourth quarter of 2007 requiring the mayor to appoint an 11-member review panel to monitor the city's compliance with the 2005 ordinance.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In May 2019, Denver became the first U.S. city to decriminalize psilocybin mushrooms after an initiative passed with 50.6% of the vote.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The measure prohibits Denver from using any resources to prosecute adults over 21 for personal use of psilocybin mushrooms, though such use remains illegal under federal law, and was legalized in the state in 2022.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver hosted the 2008 Democratic National Convention, which was the centennial of the city's first hosting of the landmark 1908 convention.
[src:denver/denver-p02] It also hosted the G7 summit between June 20 and 22 in 1997 and the 2000 National Convention of the Green Party.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In 1972, 1981, and 2008, Denver also hosted the Libertarian Party of the United States National Convention.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The 1972 Convention was notable for nominating Tonie Nathan for vice president, the first woman, as well as the first Jew, to receive an electoral vote in a United States presidential election.
[src:denver/denver-p02] On October 3, 2012, the University of Denver hosted the first of the three 2012 presidential debates between President Barack Obama and former Massachusetts Governor Mitt Romney.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In July 2019, Mayor Hancock said that Denver would not assist United States Immigration and Customs Enforcement agents with immigration raids.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The City and County of Denver levies an occupational privilege tax (OPT or head tax) on employers and employees.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver Public Schools (DPS) is the public school system in all of Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p02] It educates approximately 92,000 students in 92 elementary schools, 44 K-8 schools, 34 middle schools, 18 high schools, and 19 charter schools.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The first school of what is now DPS was a log cabin that opened in 1859, which later became East High School.
[src:denver/denver-p02] East High School, along with the other three directional high schools (West, North, and South), made up the first four high schools in Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The district boundaries are coextensive with the city limits.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Cherry Creek School District serves some areas with Denver postal addresses that are outside the city limits.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver's many colleges and universities range in age and study programs.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Three major public schools constitute the Auraria Campus: the University of Colorado Denver, Metropolitan State University of Denver, and Community College of Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The private University of Denver was the first institution of higher learning in the city and was founded in 1864.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Other prominent Denver higher education institutions include Johnson & Wales University, Catholic (Jesuit) Regis University, and the city has Roman Catholic and Jewish institutions, as well as a health sciences school.
[src:denver/denver-p02] In addition to those schools within the city, there are a number of schools throughout the surrounding metro area.
[src:denver/denver-p02] The Denver metropolitan area is served by a variety of media outlets in print, radio, television, and the Internet.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver is the 16th-largest market in the country for television, according to the 2009–2010 rankings from Nielsen Media Research.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver is also served by over 40 AM and FM radio stations, covering a wide variety of formats and styles.
[src:denver/denver-p02] 19 market in the United States, according to the Spring 2011 Arbitron ranking (up from No.
[src:denver/denver-p02] For a list of Denver radio stations, see List of radio stations in Colorado.
[src:denver/denver-p02] After continued rivalry between Denver's two main newspapers, *The Denver Post* and the *Rocky Mountain News*, the papers merged operations in 2001 under a joint operating agreement that formed the Denver Newspaper Agency.
[src:denver/denver-p02] This arrangement lasted until February 2009 when the E.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Scripps Company, the owner of the *Rocky Mountain News*, closed the paper.
[src:denver/denver-p02] There are also several alternative or localized newspapers published in Denver, including the *Westword*, *Law Week Colorado*, *Out Front Colorado,* and the *Intermountain Jewish News*.
[src:denver/denver-p02] Denver is home to multiple regional magazines such as *5280*, which takes its name from the city's mile-high elevation (5,280 feet or 1,609 meters).
[src:denver/denver-p02] The *Colorado Times News* is a Korean-language publication based in Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Most of Denver has a straightforward street grid oriented to the four cardinal directions.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Blocks are usually identified in hundreds from the median streets, identified as "00", which are Broadway (the east–west median, running north–south) and Ellsworth Avenue (the north–south median, running east–west).
[src:denver/denver-p03] Colfax Avenue, a major east–west artery through Denver, is 15 blocks (1500) north of the median.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Avenues north of Ellsworth are numbered (with the exception of Colfax Avenue and several others, such as Martin Luther King, Jr.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Blvd and Montview Blvd.), while avenues south of Ellsworth are named.
[src:denver/denver-p03] There is also an older downtown grid system that was designed to be parallel to the confluence of the South Platte River and Cherry Creek.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Most of the streets downtown and in LoDo run northeast–southwest and northwest–southeast.
[src:denver/denver-p03] This system has an unplanned benefit for snow removal; if the streets were in a normal N–S/E–W grid, only the N–S streets would receive sunlight.
[src:denver/denver-p03] With the grid oriented to the diagonal directions, the NW–SE streets receive sunlight to melt snow in the morning and the NE–SW streets receive it in the afternoon.
[src:denver/denver-p03] This idea was from Henry Brown the founder of the Brown Palace Hotel.
[src:denver/denver-p03] There is now a plaque across the street from the Brown Palace Hotel that honors this idea.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The NW–SE streets are numbered, while the NE–SW streets are named.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The named streets start at the intersection of Colfax Avenue and Broadway with the block-long Cheyenne Place.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The numbered streets start underneath the Colfax and I-25 viaducts.
[src:denver/denver-p03] There are 27 named and 44 numbered streets on this grid.
[src:denver/denver-p03] There are also a few vestiges of the old grid system in the normal grid, such as Park Avenue, Morrison Road, and Speer Boulevard.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Larimer Street, named after William Larimer Jr., the founder of Denver, which is in the heart of LoDo, is the oldest street in Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p03] All roads in the downtown grid system are streets (e.g., 16th Street, Stout Street), except for the five NE–SW roads nearest the intersection of Colfax Avenue and Broadway: Cheyenne Place, Cleveland Place, Court Place, Tremont Place and Glenarm Place.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Roads outside that system that travel east–west are designated "avenues" and those that travel north–south are designated "streets" (e.g., Colfax Avenue, Lincoln Street).
[src:denver/denver-p03] Boulevards are higher capacity streets and travel any direction (more commonly north and south).
[src:denver/denver-p03] Smaller roads are sometimes referred to as places, drives (though not all drives are smaller capacity roads; some are major thoroughfares), or courts.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Most streets outside the area between Broadway and Colorado Boulevard are organized alphabetically from the city's center.
[src:denver/denver-p03] East of Colorado Boulevard, the naming convention of streets takes on a predictable pattern of going through the alphabet by using each letter twice (i.e.
[src:denver/denver-p03] AA, BB, CC, DD, through YY – there is no Z).
[src:denver/denver-p03] The first street is almost always named after a plant or fruit, the second street is almost always named after a foreign place or location.
[src:denver/denver-p03] For example, Jersey Street / Jasmine Street, Quebec Street / Quince Street, and Syracuse Street / Spruce Street.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Inexplicably, the letter Y only has one street (Yosemite), and there is no Z.
[src:denver/denver-p03] This double-alphabet naming convention continues in some form into Aurora, Colorado.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Some Denver streets have bicycle lanes, leaving a patchwork of disjointed routes throughout the city.
[src:denver/denver-p03] There are over 850 miles (1,370 km) of paved, off-road, bike paths in Denver parks and along bodies of water, like Cherry Creek and the South Platte.
[src:denver/denver-p03] This allows for a significant portion of Denver's population to be bicycle commuters and has led to Denver being known as a bicycle-friendly city.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Some residents strongly oppose bike lanes, which has caused some plans to be watered down or nixed.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The review process for one bike line on Broadway will last over a year before city council members will make a decision.
[src:denver/denver-p03] In addition to the many bike paths, Denver launched B-Cycle – a citywide bicycle sharing program – in late April 2010.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The B-Cycle network was the largest in the United States at the time of its launch, boasting 400 bicycles.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The Denver Boot, a car-disabling device, was first used in Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The League of American Bicyclists rated Colorado as the sixth most bicycle-friendly state in the nation for 2024.
[src:denver/denver-p03] This is due in large part to Front Range cities like Boulder, Fort Collins and Denver placing an emphasis on legislation, programs and infrastructure developments that promote cycling as a mode of transportation.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Walk Score has rated Denver as the fourth most bicycle-friendly large city in the United States.
[src:denver/denver-p03] According to data from the 2011 American Community Survey, Denver ranks 6th among US cities with populations over 400,000 in terms of the percentage of workers who commute by bicycle at 2.2% of commuters.
[src:denver/denver-p03] B-Cycle – Denver's citywide bicycle sharing program – was the largest in the United States at the time of its launch in 2010, boasting 400 bicycles.
[src:denver/denver-p03] B-Cycle ridership peaked in 2014, then steadily declined.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The program announced it would cease operations at the end of January 2020.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The city announced plans to seek one or more new contractors to run a bike-share program starting mid-2020.
[src:denver/denver-p03] In 2018, e-scooter services began to place scooters in Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Hundreds of unsanctioned LimeBike and Bird electric scooters appeared on Denver streets in May, causing an uproar.
[src:denver/denver-p03] In June, the city ordered the companies to remove them and acted quickly to create an official program, including a requirement that scooters be left at RTD stops and out of the public right-of-way.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Lime and Bird scooters then reappeared in late July, with limited compliance.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Uber's Jump e-bikes arrived in late August, followed by Lyft's nationwide electric scooter launch in early September.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Lyft says that it will, each night, take the scooters to the warehouse for safety checks, maintenance and charging.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Additionally, Spin and Razor each were permitted to add 350 scooters.
[src:denver/denver-p03] 2017 rankings by Walk Score placed Denver twenty-sixth among 108 U.S. cities with a population of 200,000 or greater.
[src:denver/denver-p03] City leaders have acknowledged the concerns of walkability advocates that Denver has serious gaps in its sidewalk network.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The 2019 "Denver Moves: Pedestrians" plan outlines a need for approximate $1.3 billion in sidewalk funding, plus $400 million for trails.
[src:denver/denver-p03] In 2015, 9.6 percent of Denver households lacked a car, and in 2016, this was virtually unchanged (9.4 percent).
[src:denver/denver-p03] The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Denver averaged 1.62 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Denver is primarily served by the interstate freeways I-25 and I-70.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The problematic intersection of the two interstates is referred to locally as "the mousetrap" because, when viewed from the air, the junction (and subsequent vehicles) resemble mice in a large trap.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Denver also has a nearly complete beltway known as "the 470's".
[src:denver/denver-p03] These are SH 470 (also known as C-470), a freeway in the southwest Metro area, and two toll highways, E-470 (from southeast to northeast) and Northwest Parkway (from terminus of E-470 to US 36).
[src:denver/denver-p03] SH 470 was intended to be I-470 and built with federal highway funds, but the funding was redirected to complete conversion of downtown Denver's 16th Street to a pedestrian mall.
[src:denver/denver-p03] As a result, construction was delayed until 1980 after state and local legislation was passed.
[src:denver/denver-p03] I-470 was also once called "The Silver Stake Highway", from Gov.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Lamm's declared intention to drive a silver stake through it and kill it.
[src:denver/denver-p03] A highway expansion and transit project for the southern I-25 corridor, dubbed T-REX (Transportation Expansion Project), was completed on November 17, 2006.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The project installed wider and additional highway lanes, and improved highway access and drainage.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The project also includes a light rail line that traverses from downtown to the south end of the metro area at Lincoln Avenue.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The project spanned almost 19 miles (31 km) along the highway with an additional line traveling parallel to part of I-225, stopping just short of Parker Road.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Metro Denver highway conditions can be accessed on the Colorado Department of Transportation COtrip website.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Mass transportation throughout the Denver metropolitan area is managed and coordinated by the Regional Transportation District (RTD).
[src:denver/denver-p03] RTD operates more than 1,000 buses serving over 10,000 bus stops in 38 municipal jurisdictions in eight counties around the Denver and Boulder metropolitan areas.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Additionally, RTD operates ten rail lines, the A, B, D, E, G, H, L, N, R, and W, with a total of 113 miles (182 km) of track, serving 77 stations, 35 of which are located within the City of Denver proper.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The D, E, H, L, R, and W Lines are light rail while the A, B, G, and N Lines are commuter rail.
[src:denver/denver-p03] FasTracks is a commuter rail, light rail, and bus expansion project approved by voters in 2004, which will serve neighboring suburbs and communities.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The W Line, or West line, opened in April 2013 serving Golden/Federal Center.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The commuter rail A Line from Denver Union Station to Denver International Airport opened in April 2016 with ridership exceeding RTD's early expectations.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The light rail R Line through Aurora opened in February 2017.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The G Line to the suburb of Arvada (originally planned to open in the Fall of 2016) opened on April 26, 2019.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The N Line to Commerce City and Thornton opened on September 21, 2020.
[src:denver/denver-p03] An express bus service, known as the Flatiron Flyer, serves to connect Boulder and Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The service, billed as bus rapid transit, has been accused of bus rapid transit creep for failing to meet the majority of BRT requirements, including level boarding and all-door entry.
[src:denver/denver-p03] A commuter rail connection to Boulder and its suburb of Longmont, also part of the FasTracks ballot initiative and an extension of the B Line, is planned to be finished by RTD, but no construction funds have yet been identified prior to 2040.
[src:denver/denver-p03] RTD is currently considering an interim commuter service which would run rush-hour trains from Longmont to Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The Colorado Department of Transportation runs Bustang, a bus system that offers weekday and weekend service connecting Denver with many locations across the state, including Grand Junction, Colorado Springs, Fort Collins, and Gunnison.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Greyhound Lines, the intercity bus operator, has a major hub in Denver, with routes to New York City, Portland, Reno, Las Vegas, and their headquarters, Dallas.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Subsidiary Autobuses Americanos provides service to El Paso.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Allied bus operators Express Arrow, and Burlington Trailways provide service to Billings, Omaha, Indianapolis, and Alamosa.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Amtrak, the national passenger rail system, provides service to Denver, operating its *California Zephyr* daily in both directions between Chicago and Emeryville, California, across the bay from San Francisco.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Amtrak Thruway service operated by private bus companies links the Denver station with Rocky Mountain points.
[src:denver/denver-p03] In 2017 the Colorado legislature reinvigorated studies of passenger rail service along the Front Range, potentially connecting Denver to Fort Collins and Pueblo, or further to Amtrak connections in Cheyenne, Wyoming and Trinidad.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Front Range Passenger Rail is a current proposal (as of 2023) to link the cities from Pueblo in the south, north to Fort Collins and possibly to Cheyenne, Wyoming.
[src:denver/denver-p03] At Albuquerque, New Mexico, Denver Thruway connections are made daily with the Amtrak *Southwest Chief*.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Additionally, the Ski Train operated on the former Denver & Rio Grande Western Railroad, which took passengers between Denver and the Winter Park Ski Resort, but it is no longer in service.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The Ski Train made its final run to Winter Park on March 29, 2009.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The service was revived on a trial basis in 2016 with a great amount of local fanfare.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Further development of a mountain corridor rail option, though publicly popular, has been met with resistance from politicians, namely the director of Colorado Department of Transportation.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The Ski Train did return to service under Amtrak with the name "Winter Park Express" in 2017 and greatly expanded service for the 2024-2025 ski season, doubling capacity and increasing service to run Thursday-Monday during the winter ski seasons.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The Colorado Department of Transportation plans to eventually expand service to Steamboat Springs and Craig as part of the Mountain Rail project.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Denver's early years as a major train hub of the west are still very visible today.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Trains stop in Denver at historic Union Station, where travelers can access RTD's 16th Street Free MallRide or use light rail to tour the city.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Union Station will also serve as the main juncture for rail travel in the metro area, at the completion of FasTracks.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The city also plans to invest billions to bringing frequent public transit within one-fourth of a mile of most of its residents.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The average amount of time people spend commuting on public transit in Denver and Boulder, Colorado—for example, to and from work, on a weekday—is 77 minutes; 31% of public transit riders ride for more than two hours every day.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The average amount of time people wait at a stop or station for public transit is 14 minutes, while 25% of riders wait for over 20 minutes, on average, every day.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The average distance people usually ride in a single trip with public transit is 6.96 miles (11.20 km), while 31% travel over 7.46 miles (12.01 km) in a single direction.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Denver International Airport (IATA: DEN, ICAO: KDEN), commonly known as DIA, serves as the primary airport for the Front Range Urban Corridor surrounding Denver.
[src:denver/denver-p03] DIA is 18.6 miles (30 km) east-northeast of the Colorado State Capitol and opened in 1995.
[src:denver/denver-p03] DIA is the 3rd busiest airport in the world with 58.8 million passengers in 2021; it had the 5th highest number of passengers in the U.S., 61 million, in the pre-pandemic year 2019.
[src:denver/denver-p03] It is the largest airport by land area in the United States.
[src:denver/denver-p03] DIA serves as a major hub for United Airlines, is the headquarters and primary hub for Frontier Airlines, and is a major focus city and the fastest-growing market for Southwest Airlines.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Three general aviation airports serve the Denver area.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Rocky Mountain Metropolitan Airport (KBJC) is 13.7 miles (22 km) north-northwest, Centennial Airport (KAPA) is 13.7 miles (22 km) south-southeast, and Colorado Air and Space Port (KCFO), formerly Front Range Airport, is 23.7 miles (38 km) east of the state capitol.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Centennial Airport also offers limited commercial airline service, on two cargo airlines.
[src:denver/denver-p03] In the past, Denver has been home to several other airports that are no longer operational.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Stapleton International Airport was closed in 1995 when it was replaced by DIA.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Lowry Air Force Base was a military flight training facility that ceased flight operations in 1966, with the base finally closing in 1994.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Both Stapleton and Lowry have since been redeveloped into primarily residential neighborhoods.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Buckley Space Force Base is the only military facility in the Denver area.
[src:denver/denver-p03] Denver's relationship with Brest, France, began in 1948, making it the second-oldest sister city in the United States.
[src:denver/denver-p03] In 1947, Amanda Knecht, a teacher at East High School, visited World War II–ravaged Brest.
[src:denver/denver-p03] When she returned, she shared her experiences in the city with her students, and her class raised $32,000 to help rebuild the children's wing of Brest's hospital.
[src:denver/denver-p03] The gift led to the development of the sister city program with Brest.
[src:denver/denver-p03] There were serious efforts in the early 2000s, in both Denver and Sochi, Russian Federation, to establish sister-city ties, but the negotiations did not come to fruition.
